        <div n="430-1351" type="poem"><head type="note" n="1" xml:id="spp-430-1351-headnote-1"><lg n="1" xml:id="spp-430-1351-headnote-1-line-group-1" type="headnote"><l n="1" xml:id="spp-430-1351-headnote-1-line-group-1-line-1"/></lg></head><head type="note" n="2" xml:id="spp-430-1351-headnote-2"><lg n="1" xml:id="spp-430-1351-headnote-2-line-group-1" type="headnote"><l n="1" xml:id="spp-430-1351-headnote-2-line-group-1-line-1"/></lg></head><head type="note" n="3" xml:id="spp-430-1351-headnote-3"><lg n="1" xml:id="spp-430-1351-headnote-3-line-group-1" type="headnote"><l n="1" xml:id="spp-430-1351-headnote-3-line-group-1-line-1"/></lg></head>
      <lg n="1" type="stanza"><l n="1" xml:id="spp-430-1351-line-1"><hi rend="display-initial">U</hi>N<hi rend="SMALL-CAPS">DER</hi> this stone lie Dicky and Dolly;</l><l n="2" xml:id="spp-430-1351-line-2"> Doll dying first, Dick grew melancholy;</l><l n="3" xml:id="spp-430-1351-line-3"> For Dick without Doll thought living a folly.</l></lg><lg n="2" type="stanza"><l n="4" xml:id="spp-430-1351-line-4">Dick lost in Doll a wife tender and dear,&#13;</l><l n="5" xml:id="spp-430-1351-line-5"> But Dick lost by Doll twelve hundred a year,</l><l n="6" xml:id="spp-430-1351-line-6"> A loss that Dick thought no mortal could bear.</l></lg><lg n="3" type="stanza"><l n="7" xml:id="spp-430-1351-line-7">Dick sigh'd for his Doll, and his mournful arms crost;&#13;</l><l n="8" xml:id="spp-430-1351-line-8"> Thought much of his Doll, and the jointure he lost:</l><l n="9" xml:id="spp-430-1351-line-9"> The first vex'd him much, the other vex'd most.</l></lg><lg n="4" type="stanza"><l n="10" xml:id="spp-430-1351-line-10">Thus loaded with grief, Dick sigh'd and he cry'd;&#13;</l><l n="11" xml:id="spp-430-1351-line-11"> To live without both full three days he try'd:</l><l n="12" xml:id="spp-430-1351-line-12"> But lik'd neither loss, and so quietly dy'd.<gap/><gap/><gap/></l></lg><lg n="5" type="stanza"><l n="13" xml:id="spp-430-1351-line-13">Dick left a pattern few will copy after:&#13;</l><l n="14" xml:id="spp-430-1351-line-14"> Then, reader, pray shed some tears of salt water;</l><l n="15" xml:id="spp-430-1351-line-15"> For so sad a tale is no subject of laughter.</l></lg><lg n="6" type="stanza"><l n="16" xml:id="spp-430-1351-line-16">M──th smiles for the jointure, tho' gotten so late;&#13;</l><l n="17" xml:id="spp-430-1351-line-17"> The son laughs that got the hard-gotten estate;</l><l n="18" xml:id="spp-430-1351-line-18"> And <ref target="#spp-430-1351-footnote-1">1</ref><note place="foot" n="1" xml:id="spp-430-1351-footnote-1">General G────ges's son in-law.</note> Cuff grins, for getting the Alicant plate.</l></lg><lg n="7" type="stanza"><l n="19" xml:id="spp-430-1351-line-19">Here quiet they lie, in hopes to rise one day,&#13;</l><l n="20" xml:id="spp-430-1351-line-20"> Both solemnly put in this hole on a Sunday,</l><l n="21" xml:id="spp-430-1351-line-21"> And here rest; <hi rend="underline">sic transit gloria mundi</hi>.430-1351   </l></lg></div>
      </div>
